<HEADLINE>
<P>
SELF-HELP 2000 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A response to a book review by Dick Roraback on "The Celestine Prophecy" ("In 
Brief," May 15). 
</P>
<P>
 Books like "The Celestine Prophecy" are much needed to counteract fear-based 
ideas, while this review seems to exemplify the negativity illustrated in the 
book.It contains more information and is easier to read than most self-help 
books. The abstract fictional story can attract readers interested in novels, 
adventure and fantasy, while also teaching important concepts. Who knows -- one 
slight shift for one individual could affect many others. 
</P>
<P>
 ELLEN TEWS, LA MIRADA 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Roraback missed the point! This is a parable clothed in a fantastical 
adventure. I liked the book very much and it has made quite an impact on me and 
my friends. We are striving to put its non-new but worthy principles to work to 
improve our lives. I'm thrilled that it's on the best seller list because it 
means that many people are striving to become more human and to create 
much-needed harmony on this planet, if not by 2000 AD, then as soon as 
possible. 
</P>
<P>
 LAUREN O. THYME, RIVERSIDE 
</P>
