<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITICS' PICKS: 'IN THE LINE OF FIRE' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kenneth Turan 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 With Clint Eastwood starring as a veteran Secret Service agent in Wolfgang 
Petersen's crisply entertaining 1993 movie, the key question is who gets to 
play the implacable assassin sworn to drop the President. The choice was John 
Malkovich, who received a well-deserved Oscar nomination for his efforts in 
providing an insinuating, intrinsically adversarial presence, an ideal foil for 
Eastwood's bluntly straightforward delivery.Traumatized ever since the killing 
of J.F.K., Eastwood's Frank Horrigan wants to be on hand when Malkovich makes 
his try. Petersen brings many of the same qualities to the film as Eastwood 
himself would: a lean, unadorned style, a concern with pace and an 
understanding of genre. Petersen, best know for the splendid "Das Boot," is as 
good a match for Eastwood on his side of the camera as Malkovich is on his 
(Showtime Sunday at 8 p.m., Saturday at 8 p.m.). Kenneth Turan 
</P>
