<HEADLINE>
<P>
NO KIDDING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Shawn Hubler's "Home Away From Home" (June 5) on too-precious-for-words 
Mendocino was your most valuable offering in months. Parents need to be warned 
about these places, just as they need to know about health, weather and war 
zones.Our children have been welcome at restaurants and B&B's in Canada and 
Europe; Mendocino's preponderance of kid-hostile B&B's reflect a deplorable 
attitude more common in some U.S. establishments. 
</P>
<P>
 SANDY HACK, Culver City 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 As one of the innkeepers in Mendocino I realize the importance of catering to 
families. We have tailored a number of our rooms to accommodate families and 
welcome children of any age in our dining rooms. There is so much history in 
our town, and so much beauty, that we would hate for any child not to visit. 
</P>
<P>
 DALE STANDFAST, General Manager, Mendocino Hotel 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 I can't begin to tell you how much I enjoyed reading of Shawn Hubler's trip to 
Mendocino. In fact, I've read it over twice and laughed many times. Many thanks 
for sharing such a delightful vacation with us. I'm going to read it again! 
</P>
<P>
 RUTH B. KINGSLEY, Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA071094-0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 059297 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
